## Architecture Reference (Aspirational Patterns)

@ARCHITECTURE.md

## Project Structure & Module Organization

- `app/` holds Rails code (models, controllers, views, jobs, aspects).
- `spec/` contains RSpec tests (e.g., `spec/models`, `spec/requests`).
- `config/` stores Rails configuration, including `config/ci.rb` and `config/database.yml`.
- `db/` has migrations and schema; `storage/` is for Active Storage.
- Frontend assets use import maps (`config/importmap.rb`) and SASS via `dartsass-rails`.

## Development Commands

This project uses [mise](https://mise.jdx.dev/) to manage the Ruby version and gem paths.

### Setup and Server

- `bin/setup` installs gems, prepares the database, and starts dev services.
- `bin/dev` runs the Procfile (`Procfile.dev`) with a Rails server and SASS watcher.

### Testing

- `bin/rspec` runs the full test suite
- `bin/rspec spec/path/file_spec.rb` runs a single test file
- `bin/ci` runs style and security checks (Rubocop, bundler-audit, importmap audit, Brakeman)

### Linting

- `bin/rubocop` should not show any errors or warnings
- `bin/reek` these warnings are simply suggestions, and should be considered, but may be
  ignored if they make the code worse. Do not add `:reek:` comments to suppress warnings.

### Database

- `bin/rails db:reset` Drop, create, re-run migrations, seed
- `bin/rails db:prepare` Initializes or migrates the database.

When adding migrations, do not write the file directly. Instead, use `bin/rails
generate migration NameOfMigration` and edit the file. This uses our template with better defaults,
and avoids an issue with the timestamp in the filename generated by agents.

